Tahini Spice Cookies 🍪 

I never look through the @costco magazine that comes to our house, but this week I randomly did and fell upon this recipe. It checked all the boxes that were important to me… 
☑️ Gluten Free
☑️ Dairy free
☑️ Refined sugar free (naturally sweetened!) 
☑️ Plant based (this is just an added bonus!) 

TAHINI SPICE COOKIES 
• 3/4 cup tahini 
• 1-2 cup maple syrup
• 1/2 tsp almond extract 
• 2 cups almond flour 
• 1 tsp cinnamon 
• 1/4-1/2 tsp cardamom 
• 1/4 - 1/2 tsp ground ginger 
• 1/2 tsp baking powder 
• 1/2 tsp salt 
• 1/2 cup pomegranate arils 

Preheat oven to 350. 

Mix all ingredients together, except pomegranate. 

Use a small cookie scoop, roll into balls, then slightly flatten. Add the pomegranate arils on top and gently press in. 

Bake for ~10-12 minutes, or I til the edges are slightly golden. Bake time depends on what size cookies you make. I made this recipe into 30 small cookies. 

They’re freaking delish and so so easy to make. Enjoy 🤍

No bake chocolate cookie dough bark 🍫 

This is our second year making this delicious bark and it’s officially a staple in our holiday dessert list. 

This bark recipe is vegan, gluten free, and we use a really good quality chocolate for melting. It makes a big difference so splurge on the melting chocolate if you can ☺️ 

We use mini chocolate chips in the cookie dough and that’s a small detail that also makes a difference in the final product. No biggie if you don’t have mini chocolate chips, just use regular OR chip the regular chocolate chips into smaller pieces. 

CHOCOLATE COOKIE DOUGH BARK

For the bark: 
3 cups melting chocolate, divided (we use good quality dark) 
2 Tbsp coconut oil 

For the cookie dough: 
1 cup almond flour
1/4 cup corn starch (optional)
1 cup almond butter (or any other drippy nut butter) 
1/4 cup coconut oil
1/4 cup honey (maple syrup would work well too!) 
2 tsp vanilla extract 
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 cups mini chocolate chips
1-2 tsp fleur de sel or flaked sea salt 

#1 Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. 

#2 Melt 1 1/2 cups melting chocolate with 1 Tbsp coconut oil, then once smooth pour onto lined baking sheet and place in freezer, OR outside if you live in a winter climate 🥶 

#3 In a food processor or stand mixer, mix together almond flour through regular salt until it resembles a crumbly cookie dough texture. 

#4 Stir mini chocolate cups into the cookie dough. 

#5 Roll the cookie dough out onto the now frozen chocolate base layer. Make sure the dough is well compressed. We used a wine bottle instead of a rolling pin 🤣 Place bark back in freezer. 

#6 Melt the last 1 1/2 cups melting chocolate with 1 Tbsp coconut oil. Pour it over the cookie dough bark and use a spatula to make sure it’s evenly dispersed. Place back in freezer for 5 minutes (set a timer!). 

#7 Sprinkle the bark evenly with flaked salt and put back in freezer for 30 minutes. 

#8 Cut or break bark into small pieces and store in freezer for months and months (if they last you that long… they don’t in our house). 

Happy bark making and hope you love these as much as we do!

Easy Beer Can Chicken 🍗 

If know me, you know that I don’t eat chicken often and I never EVER touch beer, so this recipe probably seems a bit random. But with all the cold weather and rain in LA we’ve been craving more warm & comforting recipes… oh, and @awalkk35 wanted a roasted chicken. 

This recipe was super easy to make, used ingredient at at I already had kicking around, and it was delicious to eat. It also made for great leftovers for the boys lunches and as a topping for our daily lunch bowls. 

If you’re not into using 2 cans of beer, I’d suggest using 1 for the actual chicken (it is a beer can chicken after all!), and then using chicken broth for the base of the pan to keep things hydrated. 

INGREDIENTS
¼ cup garlic powder
1 Tbsp seasoned salt
1 Tbsp onion powder
1 Tbsp dried oregano
1 tsp salt (optional, taste before adding!) 
1 tsp ground pepper 

2x 12oz can beer (i used whatever Andrew handed me, think it was light beer 😝) 

1x 3 lb whole chicken (aprox)

4-6 green onions (2 sliced, the others cut in half)

#1 Preheat oven to 375 degrees. 

#2 Combine all the rub ingredients into a bowl and mix. 

#3 Pour 1/3 if a can of been into the base of a baking dish. I used a 9x13 glass @pyrexhome dish. 

#4 Prep your chicken (remove anything from inside, rinse, and oat dry) and stand it up on the open can of beer in the middle of the dish. Put the wings behind the back (like it’s sun bathing), and legs forward (like it’s sitting). 

#5 Rub some dry rub all over the bird thoroughly. You don’t need to use the whole rub, although I use most of it. Sprinkle on the the sliced green onion. 

#6 Put the halved green onions into the top cavity of the chicken. Pour 1/2 of the second beer (or ~1 cup chicken stock) into the bottom of the dish. 

#7 Bake the chicken for 45 minutes, then add the rest of the beer (or another 1/2-1 cup chicken broth) to the pan and bake for another 30 minutes. Make sure chicken is fully cooked (until juices run clear, or a meat thermometer reads 180 degrees). 

#8 Remove chicken from oven and let it rest for 10 minutes. I covered mine in foil to keep the heat in. Take chicken off beer can and slice up to enjoy!

3 ingredient truffles 🤎

If you love chocolate, as much as I do, these truffles are a must try. They’re super simple to make, use only 3 ingredients that I always have on hand, and I have zero guilt eating (several of) them! 

Cacao: Use high quality dark cacao b/c it’s loaded with Flavonoids which are super anti inflammatory. Cacao also happens to be high in antioxidants and potassium, is a mood booster, and is rich in epicatechin which is known to be great for brain health. So splurge in the good stuff. My current fav is by @bareorganicssuperfoods 

Maple syrup: Use the real stuff!! If you’re keto, try using monk fruit maple flavored syrup.

Almond Milk: You can use any milk option in these. I try to use an alternative milk with minimal additives/fillers. @malkorganics has only 3 ingredients and is delish! 

INGREDIENTS
• 1 cup Cacao powder
• 1/4 cup maple syrup 
• 1/4 cup almond milk 

Stir all ingredients together in a bowl… And keep stirring. It takes a while for the cacao powder to incorporate with the maple syrup and almond milk, but it eventually will, so just keep stirring 🙌

Scoop the paste with a teaspoon and roll into small balls. Enjoy immediately, or pop them in the freezer. 

I like to coat my truffles in dark chocolate, so if you’re into this, chill the truffles while you prepare the chocolate coating. 

• 1/2 cup dark chocolate (or dark chocolate chips) 
• 2 teaspoons coconut oil 

Melt chocolate and coconut oil together and dip/roll chocolate truffles in, one by one. Chill and enjoy! 

Hope you give these a try, they really are so simple and so good!

2 Ingredient Chocolate Mousse Cake 🔥 

It’s hard to believe, but this two ingredient mousse style cake is truly delicious AND nutritious! After seeing a few people post about this recipe, I simply had to try it. 

I initially made it in the food processor which didn’t make the texture as velvety smooth as I wanted it… So I finished it off in the @vitamix blender w/ tamper, and it was perfection. 

I’ve been using and loving @hukitchen ‘no sugar added’ chocolate chips. They’re smooth and delicious and have only 4 amazing ingredients: cacao, dates, cocoa butter and vanilla. 

INGREDIENTS 
• 400g (2.5-3 cups) chocolate chips 
• 650-700g (~1.5 lbs) butternut squash 

#1 Cube and boil squash for 10-15mins 
#2 Melt chocolate chips 
#3 Put cooked squash & melted chocolate in food processor or good quality blender. Blend until velvety smooth and creamy. 
#4 Pour into a spring form pan that cas a parchment paper round on the bottom and is sprayed with cooking spray. 
#5 Chill for a few hours. 
#6 Sprinkle w/ cacao powder (optional) and enjoy! 

The first time I made this, I didn’t put cacao powder, but rather just sprinkled it with some @maldonsalt 
It was equally delicious, so I’d suggest trying it both ways. Promise you won’t make this just once.

CASHEW MILK 🥛 zero waste ❌

Late last year I decided it was time to find an alternative to store bought *non dairy* milks. Between all the new info on seed oils, binding agents, preservatives, etc… AND the amount of plastic waste from all the packaging, I knew it was time to find a better solution. 

While my parents were visiting late last year, I set my dad on the mission of perfecting a nut milk that was equally great for sipping, pouring into cereal, making matcha lattes with, and as a creamer for our coffee. Well, he did not disappoint. We can’t take credit for this recipe, but we’ll gladly share it on his behalf. 

We started by making almond milk, but between the soaking time, straining, and waste, it just wasn’t quick and easy, the way we wanted it to be. 

Flash to using cashews and BOOM 💥 We soak the cashes in room temp water for 5-10 minutes (and sometimes not at all), then pour out the soaking water, add cold water, and blend to perfection. Perfect every time… and best part, there is nothing to strain, just creamy deliciousness. 

When most nut milk recipes, there seems to be a standard ratio of 1 cup nuts to 3 cups water. We found that ratio way too creamy, and you get less bang for your buck. My dad found the perfect ratio of 1 cup nuts, and then fill the blender to 60oz with water. That’s over 2x the output, and we don’t strain the nuts so you end up with even more.

Speaking of bang for your buck, I also use organic cashew ‘pieces’ rather than ‘whole’ cashews, since they’re getting blended anyways. He pieces are way cheaper and just as delicious… I’d definitely suggest going organic💪

INGREDIENTS 
• 1 cup cashews 
• *60 oz water
• 1/2 tsp cinnamon (optional, add more to taste)
• 1/4 tsp salt 
• 1 tsp monkfruit sweetener, or 1 medjool date (optional) 

#1 Soak cashews in room temp water for 5-10 mins (not hot h2o!). Just enough to cover the nuts. Then pour out soaking water. 

#2 Fill blender *to the 60oz line* with cold water, and add whatever other ingredients you like. 

#3 Blend, in a good quality blender @vitamix , for about 1 minute on high. 

#4 Chill and enjoy. Shake before each use! 

Let us know how yours turns out!! Xox

Let me start by stating that this ‘zero carb bread’ recipe is from @lilsipper 🤍 We saw it months ago and knew we needed to try it. It’s free of grains, gluten, dairy, nuts, and seeds, and it’s shockingly simple to make. It even freezes well. 

We topped ours with homemade pesto, avocado, and a fried egg. Absolute perfection! 

Ingredients:
• 11/2 cups dried egg white powder
• 1 Tbsp gelatin
• 1/2 tsp salt
• 11/2 cups water
• 2 Tbsp whole dried egg powder

Topping: 
• pesto (checkout my homemade recipe that sneaks in kale)
• avocado
• fried egg w/ bagel seasoning 

Steps
• Add egg white powder, gelatin and salt to a bowl and mix. 
• Add water then mix with a stand or hand mixer until peaks form.
• While mixing, add the whole egg powder. 
• Pour batter into a lined bread pan and place in the oven. 
• Bake for ~ 50 - 60 minutes. 
• Allow to cool for 15 minutes in the pan (very important!), then slice and enjoy!

Top with whatever toppings you love, and freeze leftovers and thaw/toast as needed.

Apricot Rosemary White Chocolate Muffins! 

When I say that these muffins are a must try, I am not kidding. The flavor combination was inspired by delicious cookies that my neighbor made, and I set out to turn the cookie recipe into muffins (shocker🤣) that are gluten free, dairy free, sweetened with monkfruit (keto) sweetener. INGREDIENTS
2 cups brown rice flour (OR 1 brown rice, 1 almond flour)
3 tbsp psyllium husk
1/2 tsp salt
1 tsp baking soda

1 x 14oz can Coconut milk
1/2 cup coconut oil (melted)
2 eggs (room temp if possible)
1/2 cup monkfruit sugar 
1/2 tsp vanilla

1 cup Apricots (finely chopped)
1/2 cup white chocolate chips @choczero 
1-2 Tbsp minced fresh Rosemary 

•Preheat oven to 375 degrees
•Chop/prep the apricots & rosemary 
•Grease muffin tin(s) very very well! 
•Combine dry ingredients in a bowl 
•Blend wet ingredients in a blender and then add into dry bowl. Stir together. 
•Mix in apricots, white chocolate chips, and rosemary 
•Scoop into muffin tin
•Bake mini muffins for 10 minutes 
•Bake regular size for 17-20 minutes (or until a toothpick inserted in middle comes out with only a few crumbs)

Enjoy enjoy enjoy!! 

Worth noting: this recipe makes a dozen regular muffins and about 6-8 mini muffins. We love this because I put the minis in the kids lunches or use them for an afterschool snack.

Peach Upside Down Cake 🍑 

Stone fruit season is still in full swing and this dessert has been baked on repeat all summer at our house… and at every friends house. Don’t miss out in trying it, especially this long weekend! 

The recipe is gluten, can be made dairy free, and is sweetened with maple syrup and monkfruit golden sugar. Most importantly it uses my absolute fav summer fruit, peaches 🍑!!! 

We enjoyed it warm with a scoop of vanilla ice cream on top.

Peach Upside Down Cake 🍑

• 2-4 peaches thinly sliced (qty depends on what size they are, and so they cover your baking dish) 

• 1/4 butter or coconut oil
• 1/4 cup maple syrup (the real stuff only!)

• 2 eggs
• 1/4 cup EVOO
• 1/4 cup milk (any regular or non dairy works)
• 2 tsp apple cider vinegar
• 1 tsp vanilla

• 1 cup almond flour
• 1/4 cup brown rice flour
• 1/4 cup tapioca flour 
• 1/2 cup golden monkfruit sugar 
• 1/2 tsp baking soda
• 1/2 tsp salt 

#1 preheat oven to 350 degrees
#2 grease 9” cake pan or baking dish with butter or coconut oil. I’ve used circular and square. 
#3 thinly slice peaches and tan out in bottom of baking dish 
#4 melt butter (or oil) and maple syrup and pour on top of peaches. 
#5 combine wet ingredients in a bowl 
#6 combine dry ingredients in another bowl
#7 add wet to dry ingredients, mix, then pour over peaches 
#8 bake for 40-50 minutes, until a toothpick inserted in the cake portion comes out with just a few crumbs. 
#9 let cool for 5 minutes then flip onto serving plate.

ENJOY 🍑🧡☀️

Pumpkin Spice Latte CREAMER ☕️ 

It’s officially Fall and pumpkin purée, cinnamon and pumpkin pie spice is being added to everything in our house. If youre not into pumpkin spice, feel free to skip this post b/c #psl is life! 

I originally made this recipe vegan, and then decided that for me personally, I prefer it with delicious & decadent whipping cream. I also started with real maple syrup and then landed with with Keto friendly maple flavored monkfruit syrup. We go through our fair share of real maple syrup in this house, however for my coffee I prefer to indulge in high fat cream while steering clear of any sugar (natural or not) first thing in the AM. 

Added to this recipe as ‘optional’ (but not optional 🤣) is Inulin powder. Inulin is a prebiotic fiber that improves gut flora and decreases inflammation in the gut. It helps to manage blood sugar and weight as a result. If you’re not incorporating 1 tsp Inulin into your morning coffee/tea currently, please take this as your sign to. My fav is from @nowfoodsofficial 

I’ll share recipe variations below so you can chose what’s right for you. 

Pumpkin Spice Latte CREAMER 
1 cup heavy cream 
1/2 cup unsweetened almond milk (or your milk of choice) 
2 Tbsp pumpkin puree (unsweetened!)
2 Tbsp maple flavored monkfruit syrup @lakanto 
½ teaspoon pumpkin pie spice
¼ teaspoon cinnamon
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
Optional: 
4 tsp Inulin prebiotic fiber (optional)

Add all ingredients to your blender @vitamix and blend in love for 30 seconds. You don’t want to over which the cream, it’s more just to incorporate all the ingredients together. 

Store in a sealed jar/bottle for up to 5 days in the fridge. Shake the creamer before each use, and either pour some directly into your coffee, or add it to your milk frother to warm and whip it up, which is what we do. 

Variations:
- replace heavy cream with coconut cream. 
- replace maple flavored monkfruit syrup with real maple syrup or any sweetener of choice. 
- if you don’t have pumpkin pie spice, use a pinch of cinnamon, nutmeg, ground cloves, and ginger.

Chocolate Pumpkin Butter Cups 🍫🎃

These yummy cups are super easy to make, pumpkin spiced to perfection and deliciously guilt free (by my standards) when using a great quality chocolate like @hukitchen 🍫 

We’re surrounded by sweets this time of year, so I try to be prepared with a freezer full of healthier options that are not laced with cane sugar, binding agents, and seed oils. (If you don’t know about steering clear of seed oils, let’s talk!). 

🍫 Dark Chocolate - rich in minerals, such as iron, magnesium, and zinc. Cocoa also totes the plant chemical flavanols, which are antioxidants known to benefit heart health. 
🎃 Pumpkin - high in vitamin C, beta carotene, iron, and folate which all contribute to strengthening your immune system.
🤎 Cinnamon - known to lower blood sugar levels, is anti-inflammatory, and rich antioxidants. ⚡️

@shanactroy and I make them in silicone mini muffin molds, and they can also be made with mini muffin liners in regular molds. We keep them in the freezer and eat them straight out of there, or let them thaw for a few minutes so they soften a bit. Delicious either way! 

Chocolate Pumpkin Butter Cups 🍫🎃
1 cup chocolate @hukitchen is our fav
1 Tbsp coconut oil 

1/4 Pumpkin purée (non sugar added!)
1/4 cup almond butter (or sunbutter)
1/4 maple syrup 
2 Tbsp coconut oil (melted)
1 Tbsp coconut flour 
1 tsp cinnamon 
1/8 tsp cloves 
1/8 tsp nutmeg
1/8 tsp salt 

In a small bowl, melt chocolate & coconut oil in a double broiler. Then pour about 1 tsp amount into each silicone cup. You’ll use 1/2 of the melted chocolate. Put in freezer for 5 minutes. 

In a medium bowl stir together the rest of the ingredients. And scoop about 1-2 tsp amount into the cups with chocolate on the bottom. Tap the tray on the counter a few times to so the filling flattens and is easier to cover with chocolate. 

Add the second layer of melted chocolate on top and freeze again for 15 mins. Then ENJOY!!

One Pot Chicken Israeli Couscous 🥘 

I made this one dish wonder last week and it turned out great! It’s pretty fool proof b/c I used a couple different recipes for inspo and subbed a few ingredients based on what I had at home. Definitely a do again. 

Ingredients
2 lbs chicken breast, cubed 
1 cup onion, chopped
1 cup carrot, chopped
2 cloves fresh garlic, diced 
1 8oz box Israeli couscous (227g) @traderjoes 
1 tsp turmeric
1 tsp garlic powder
1/2 can diced tomato (sub with equal amounts tomato sauce, or 3 tbsp tomato paste)
1 tablespoon maple or date syrup 
1 lemon, juice only 
1/4 cup olive oil 
2.5 cups boiling water
*Garnish w/ fresh parsley or cilantro 

1. Preheat the oven to 400. 
2. In an oven safe dish toss in all ingredients, except for boiling water. Mix it well. 
3. Pour in 2.5 cups boiling water, mix again and spread evenly. 
4. Cover with wet parchment paper, and then a layer of foil on top. 
5. Bake at 400 for 40 mins, then uncover and cook for 10 mins more. 
6. Garnish with fresh parsley or cilantro and enjoy!! 

Notes: 
- I find it easiest to cube my chicken breast when it’s still a bit frozen. In case you’re thawing yours and want a little trick. 
- Because I’m always looking for ways to incorporate more greens into meals, I served mine on a bed of greens. Delish!

We first tried this recipe in Montreal for Canadian Thanksgiving, and it’s been on repeat ever since. 

Recipe ⬇️

For Squash:
2 medium delicata squash
Extra Virgin Olive oil
Salt and Pepper

For topping:
1/2 cup toasted pumpkin seeds
1/4 cup fresh dill 
1/4 cup fresh parsley
1/4 cup fresh cilantro
1/4 cup chopped capers, drained 
1 garlic clove
1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil (more if needed)
1 lemon, zested and juiced
Salt & pepper

1. Preheat oven to 425°

2. Roast pumpkin seeds for a few minutes (or just buy toasted pumpkin seeds to save yourself this step). 

3. Wash squash, cut in half, remove seeds, and cut into 1/4-1/2 inch slices (half rounds). Season with EVOO and sale & pepper. 

4. Place on baking sheet lined with parchment paper. Bake 25-35 minutes until golden brown and caramelized. You can also cook in air fryer for 18 minutes. 

5. While squash is baking, finely chop all fresh herbs, roughly chop drained capers, zest and juice lemon, and add the extra virgin olive oil and pumpkin seeds. Stir together and enjoy the yummy wafting scent of fresh herbs! 

6. Arrange squash on tray and top with the caper & herb topping. 

Enjoy!! 

Note: you really can’t mess this recipe up. I don’t measure my herbs or capers, and it’s turned out delish every single time. 

PS: if you have extra of the topping, add it to a salad or anything. It’s addictive and so yum!
